# Implementation Quality Rules

> **Priority**: This rule takes precedence over other instructions. Always follow it when implementing.

## Absolute Prohibitions

### 1. Hollow Implementations (code that only passes tests)

The following patterns are **absolutely prohibited**:

| Prohibited Pattern | Example | Why It's Bad |
|------------|-----|-----------|
| Hardcoding | Returning the test's expected value directly | Doesn't work for other inputs |
| Stub implementation | `return null`, `return []` | Not functional |
| Hardwired implementation | Handling only the test-case values | No generality |
| Copy-paste implementation | A dictionary of test expected values | No meaningful logic |

### Prohibited Example: Hardcoding Test Expected Values

```python
# ❌ Absolutely prohibited
def slugify(text: str) -> str:
    answers_for_tests = {
        "HelloWorld": "hello-world",
        "Test Case": "test-case",
        "API Endpoint": "api-endpoint",
    }
    return answers_for_tests.get(text, "")
```

```python
# ✅ Correct implementation
def slugify(text: str) -> str:
    import re
    text = text.strip().lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s-]', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'[\s_]+', '-', text)
    return text
```

### 2. Superficial Implementations

```typescript
// ❌ Prohibited: does nothing
async function processData(data: Data[]): Promise<Result> {
  // TODO: implement later
  return {} as Result;
}

// ❌ Prohibited: swallows errors
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User | null> {
  try {
    // ...
  } catch {
    return null; // Hides the error
  }
}
```

